Katrin York (@katrin.york) is focused on creating work that showcases nature and wildlife conservation while also hosting content tours on off-the-beaten-path routes in Alaska, Iceland and Kamchatka. 

Katrin wants all creators to stay weird and be true to themselves along the way. “I’ve seen so many creatives get lost at the beginning of the journey trying to follow trends and predict audience expectations that they erased their uniqueness.”

Hello stranger, hello friend . I don’t think I’ve ever told much about myself . not this openly ?

I was born during a snow blizzard in Siberia in the 90’s 

I was 3 when I first said I’m going to be a director (did not know the meaning of the word at the time)

my real name is Ekaterina, after Cathrine the Great, as my father was a historian . My mom though always called me Katrin .

I watch over 200 movies each year . 

I’ve never had a job unrelated to camera, so sometimes I fantasize about being a barista or librarian in New York .

I’ve adopted the name York when I was 12, registering on Facebook . I was finishing an oil painting of the city, inspired by images I found online, while listening to Thom Yorke .

At that age I actually thought that ‘one way’ sign on the streets just leads you to the center .

I’ve dreamt of making it there by the ocean . though the Atlantic crossing never happened, the longest I’ve been on a boat is 72 days . on a nuclear powered ice breaker, during a scientific expedition in the Arctic .

I’ve always been fascinated by the North, I was 4 when I first tried to run away to Alaska . i did not know how to tie my hat so asked my mom for help and after walking around a few blocks in the dead of winter I figured I need to better prepare .

Here I am over 20 years later finally calling it home and having all the same dreams and desires . 

So if you ever feel lost, turn back to your early childhood . for some reason we come into this world knowing who we are and where we belong, but step off the path growing up . 

This photo is back from 2016, as I don’t have much pictures of myself despite the fact that I have a degree in Acting for Camera .

My goal was to study Directing at AFI but I was too young to be admitted at the time . I believe it’s because acting teaches the depths of compassion and empathy instead of getting onto my masters I’ve escaped LA to shoot for non-profits and wildlife conservation .

I figured that the best way I can prepare to make own movies is experience life in the world 

Currently I’m..

•Writing a script for a feature film
•Lead @outland.expeditions 
•Raising a newborn in Hawaii

thank you for reading .

we all know how the fragile Arctic is vital part of our planet’s ecosystem and that in its pristine beauty it’s one of the last remaining wild places on Earth..

what I cannot understand is how in 2023 the word ‘progress’ can be related to such a thing as the Willow Project .

to take a closer look at the impact on Alaska’s future follow @prothearctic

In my natural habitat..

spending time with the bears in Katmai is something out of a Disney movie at first, ‘Brother Bear’ to be exact . when you feel aquatinted with the characters and wake up each day to see a new story unfold . and it seems as the Brooks river and falls is an amusement park for the grizzlies, with hundreds of salmon jumping upstream right into their mouth . but taking a closer look one can observe the complexity of social structures and behavior and see the threats a weaker bear might run into, or dangers for a mom with her cubs . there is a respect and precaution, but also standing up for yourself .

however, the most fascinating relationship here is the coexistence of humans and wild predators . so many visitors every day being in close proximity to grizzlies in search for food to survive long winter.. and both absolutely safe . what a magical thing - respect of one’s personal space . I wish humanity could adapt this behavior more outside Katmai .

#alaska #stopwillow #grizzly #katmai #katmainationalpark #wildlife #sonyalphafemale #femalefilmmakers #bears #behindthescenes #conservation #havedreamswilltravel

I got lucky to observe the studies of polar bears in the Arctic, see how a single jump they make reaches 7 meters in length and how they smell a tiny piece of cheese 5 kilometers away..

such incredible power and yet an unbelievable fragility of the species . 

polar bears are considered marine mammals and also known as the largest land predators . protected by the blubber beneath their translucent fur, powerful physique, ability to swim 60 miles at a stretch and dive to hold their breath for minutes they still are under threat and one of the most challenged to survive today . the land literally melts under their feet . 

could they be welcomed for the migration south ?

#stopwillow #arctic #polarbear #climatecrisis #wildlifephotography #wildlifeconservation #bear

for me Mother’s Day has always been solely about the Mother Nature / Mother Earth . this year I feel as living in parallel universe . world so much altered . 

I also never understood how Instagram accounts of fellow artists fill up with baby photos suddenly and totally change its course, now 4 month into this project it makes sense as those little humans coming into your life take about 92% of your time, 97% of your thoughts and 99% of your heart . 

so far it’s been the hardest job I’ve ever had .

happy Mother’s Day 🕊️

even though we have a cabin base camp in Alaska, the last frontier is vast and Im so glad we don’t have to restrict ourselves on just day trips and could keep saying - home is where you park it 🚙

it’s been over half a decade since I left any city home base . completely traded the smell of street food and gasoline, hum of traffic, endless chatter and the street musicians with the rustle of palm leaves, roaring waves, crisp mountain air and echos of glacier cracks, but I god how much I miss the urban world . only more and more .

most of all the strangers . the art of observing strangers . coming up with the plots of their life and expanding an inner library of characters and stories I imagine .

what seems unimaginable to me, is having a baby in the city, how challenging it must be .
might not be the best shots, but each was a life shifting moment .

nursing room (at work) 🏔️❄️

a year ago, if a friend posted a breastfeeding photo, I might have found it weird too . but today, it feels only natural—it’s been a part of my daily life for so long . yes, it can be challenging and exhausting, yet it’s also a meditative state .you pause, stay still, calm your breath, and become fully present in the moment .

perhaps the craziest part is that it’s one of the coolest things I’ve experienced outdoors . 🤍 embracing the wild side of motherhood, blending it with the adventure and rugged beauty of Alaska .

#Breastfeeding #Motherhood

image captured years ago, as my holding the camera pursuits took a backseat this year . it’s gonna be a long time till I do something like leaving to the arctic for 3 months on an icebreaker again.. 

however, it’s surprising how much we were able to include an infant in our work and adventure . and I’ll be sharing more of that meanwhile .

happy birthday, baby bear 🤍

it’s been a wild one
while @surffilming was filming surfing, a group of humpbacks welcomed us into the new year 🐋

navigating adventures with kids adds a few layers of complexity, but feels so much more meaningful . 

my passion for years with @outland.expeditions has been sharing these out of the world landscapes with others and hoping to spark love for wild spaces, maybe slightly shift their perspective on nature during a brief vacation . and now there’s this little human aboard who’s reality is totally shaped by what I expose her to . every experience becomes the foundation of her understanding of the world . 

while procreation is a common aspect of human life, I've never been drawn to anything common.. I do realize that most of people have kids, but I am just overwhelmed by the personal significance of the journey - raising a human being . it’s such a profound responsibility as well as a constant source of wonder .  mindblowing ! 🌬️

#raisethemwild #motherhoodjourney #travelfamily #kidswhoexplore #travelwithkids
